= El Otatal

Figueroa was ransomed out in September by an army column; Lucio's luck has run three months longer, and is running out tonight. At a place called El Otatal, ten thousand soldiers have drawn the year's last encirclement around the schoolteacher of Atoyac and what remains of his brigade — the noose the whole campaign was built toward, closing in the dark.

If it closes, the Party of the Poor will not survive him — organizations built on one man's moral credit rarely do. What survives will come down the mountain in twos and threes over the winter: sick, hunted, eighteen and twenty years old, carrying nothing but the sierra's verdict that the armed road, for this generation, in this state, is closed. The DFS knows they will be coming down. Everyone knows. The question is who reaches them first: the Brigada, the Liga's recruiters — or a Party that never blessed their war and must now decide what it owes their peace.

[? if (via = "armada" or via = "dual") and inteligencia >= 35 : Except that this time there is an hour in which history is still wet ink: your people inside the garrisons' supply chain saw the encirclement forming two days ago, and a runner is already on the trails. Whether the warning beats the army to El Otatal is a question of hours and luck — but for once, uniquely in this war, the question exists. ?]

- @salvarlo: Spend everything on the warning: every route, every source, the whole network's cover, to get one schoolteacher off El Otatal alive.
- @recibir: Reach them first. Lawyers where there are charges, doctors where there are wounds, silence where there are neither.
- @distancia: The Party cannot become the guerrilla's convalescent home; the ones the DFS follows down will lead them through your doors.

