The runner reaches the camp at dusk with the map of the noose, and the schoolteacher — who has broken more encirclements than the army admits attempting — reads it by feel, argues it in assembly per his unbreakable custom, and moves the column at midnight through the one seam the operation left unsewn. The last brigade bleeds crossing the river; the army closes on a campsite of cold fires and photographs those instead.

The cost is enormous and itemized: two sources burned, a route abandoned forever, the Brigada suddenly, furiously aware of how deeply it is seen. And against it, a single entry that no ledger can weigh: on the third of December, 1974, in this history and no other, Lucio Cabañas is alive. The corrido writers, cheated of an ending, will have to learn to write beginnings.

